    overview: "The reticulocyte count measures the percentage or absolute number of immature red blood cells (reticulocytes) in peripheral blood. It is the best indicator of bone marrow erythropoietic activity and helps classify anemias as hyperproliferative (adequate marrow response) or hypoproliferative (inadequate marrow response).",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Reticulocytes are immature RBCs that have lost their nucleus but retain residual RNA (ribosomes). They mature in the bone marrow and are released into blood, completing maturation over 1-2 days. Residual RNA is detected by supravital stains (new methylene blue, brilliant cresyl blue) that precipitate the RNA into a visible reticular network. Automated methods use fluorescent dyes (thiazole orange) or RNA-binding dyes with flow cytometry.",
    clinicalRelevance: "Normal reticulocyte count: 0.5-2.0% (or 25,000-75,000/μL absolute). Corrected reticulocyte count = retic % × (patient Hct / 45). Reticulocyte production index (RPI) = corrected retic / maturation time correction factor. RPI >2 = adequate marrow response (hemolysis, hemorrhage). RPI <2 = inadequate response (aplastic anemia, iron/B12/folate deficiency, MDS). Automated reticulocyte parameters: IRF (immature reticulocyte fraction), MCVr, CHr (reticulocyte hemoglobin content).",
