    assessment: "Manual method: supravital stain (new methylene blue), count reticulocytes per 1,000 RBCs. Reticulocytes appear as blue precipitated RNA network within red cells. Automated: flow cytometry with fluorescent dyes—more precise and reproducible. Report: % and absolute count (absolute = % × RBC count). CHr (reticulocyte hemoglobin content): early marker of iron deficiency (decreased before MCV changes).",
    management: "Use reticulocyte count to classify anemia: elevated = hemolytic anemia or acute blood loss (marrow responding). Low/normal = production defect (iron deficiency, B12/folate deficiency, aplastic anemia, renal failure). Monitor response to treatment: reticulocyte count should rise within 3-5 days of iron/B12/folate replacement.",
    complications: "Falsely elevated: Howell-Jolly bodies, Heinz bodies, or Pappenheimer bodies may be counted as reticulocytes on manual counts. Falsely low: delayed staining, clotted specimen. RPI correction needed to account for early release of reticulocytes (shift reticulocytes) in anemic patients.",
    clinicalPearls: ["Polychromasia on Wright stain = reticulocytes—polychromatic cells are reticulocytes that appear blue-gray", "CHr (reticulocyte hemoglobin content) is the EARLIEST marker of iron deficiency—decreases before MCV", "RPI >2 indicates ADEQUATE marrow response (hemolysis, hemorrhage); RPI <2 indicates INADEQUATE response"],
    examPitfalls: ["Corrected reticulocyte count adjusts for anemia; RPI additionally corrects for shift reticulocytes (early marrow release)", "Supravital stains (new methylene blue) are NOT the same as Romanowsky stains (Wright/Giemsa)—different principle", "An elevated reticulocyte count in the setting of anemia indicates the marrow IS responding—look for hemolysis or blood loss"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "Why correct the reticulocyte count?", answer: "In anemia, the percentage is falsely elevated because there are fewer mature RBCs. Corrected retic = retic % × (patient Hct / normal Hct). RPI further corrects for early release of reticulocytes from the marrow (shift reticulocytes take longer to mature in blood)." }, { question: "What is CHr?", answer: "Reticulocyte hemoglobin content (CHr or Ret-He) measures hemoglobin in reticulocytes. It reflects iron available for erythropoiesis in the past 24-48 hours and decreases before MCV in iron deficiency, making it the earliest indicator of functional iron deficiency." }]
