    examPitfalls: ["Anemia falsely INCREASES ESR (fewer RBCs → faster sedimentation); polycythemia falsely DECREASES ESR", "CRP rises FASTER than ESR (6 hours vs 24-48 hours) and returns to normal faster—better for acute monitoring", "A tilted ESR tube gives falsely ELEVATED results—must be exactly vertical"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "Why does sickle cell disease have a low ESR?", answer: "Sickle cells have an irregular shape that prevents rouleaux formation. Without rouleaux, individual cells sediment slowly. This applies to all abnormally shaped RBCs (spherocytes, acanthocytes)." }, { question: "ESR vs CRP: when to use each?", answer: "ESR: chronic inflammatory monitoring (temporal arteritis, PMR, RA), slow to rise (24-48h) and fall. CRP: acute inflammation monitoring, rises quickly (6h) and normalizes quickly. CRP is more sensitive for acute changes; ESR is more useful for chronic conditions." }]
