    management: "Cell maturation knowledge is applied in: bone marrow differential counting, peripheral blood smear review, leukemia classification (FAB and WHO), flow cytometry interpretation.",
    complications: "Blast identification errors: reactive lymphocytes may be confused with blasts. Auer rods are NEVER found in lymphoblasts (always myeloid). Monocyte precursors may be confused with blasts on morphology.",
    clinicalPearls: ["As cells mature: size DECREASES, chromatin CONDENSES, nucleoli DISAPPEAR, N:C ratio DECREASES", "The MYELOCYTE is the last granulocytic stage capable of MITOSIS", "Auer rods are found ONLY in myeloid blasts—NEVER in lymphoblasts (key distinction AML vs ALL)"],
    examPitfalls: ["The pronormoblast is the EARLIEST recognizable erythroid precursor—not the HSC (which is morphologically indistinct)", "Primary (azurophilic) granules first appear at the PROMYELOCYTE stage; specific (secondary) granules at the MYELOCYTE stage", "Megakaryocytes undergo endomitosis (nuclear replication without cell division)—resulting in large polyploid cells"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "What is the myelocyte stage?", answer: "The myelocyte is the first stage where specific (secondary) granules appear, determining whether the cell becomes a neutrophil, eosinophil, or basophil. It is also the last stage capable of mitosis. Cells beyond this stage (metamyelocyte, band, segmented) no longer divide." }, { question: "How are myeloid and lymphoid blasts distinguished?", answer: "Morphology: Auer rods = myeloid only. Cytochemistry: myeloperoxidase (MPO) positive = myeloid. Flow cytometry: myeloid markers (CD13, CD33, CD117, MPO) vs lymphoid markers (B: CD19, CD10; T: CD3, CD7). Flow cytometry is the definitive method." }]
