    examPitfalls: ["Friedewald equation requires FASTING specimen and TG <400—otherwise use direct LDL measurement", "Refrigerated serum with a creamy layer on top indicates chylomicrons (dietary fat, non-fasting specimen)", "HDL is measured in the supernatant after PRECIPITATING all other lipoproteins (or by homogeneous direct method)"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "Why does the Friedewald equation fail at high TG?", answer: "At TG >400, the ratio of TG to cholesterol in VLDL is no longer constant (TG/5 approximation breaks down). The calculated LDL becomes inaccurate. Direct LDL measurement or the Martin-Hopkins equation should be used instead." }, { question: "Why is fasting required?", answer: "Fasting eliminates chylomicrons from the specimen. Chylomicrons contain dietary triglycerides that elevate the TG result and make the Friedewald LDL calculation inaccurate." }]
